[30;1m144 | [0m[35mencoding right in cases where the document contains a <tt class="docutils literal">&lt;meta&gt;</tt>[0m

[30;1m136 | [0m[35m<h1>Iteration</h1>[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1173[0m[34m of [0m[33m2617[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m114 | [0m[35m&gt;&lt;/d&gt;'</span>[0m
[30;1m115 | [0m[35m</pre></div>[0m
[30;1m116 | [0m[35m<p>ElementTree objects are serialised as complete documents, including[0m
[30;1m117 | [0m[35mpreceding or trailing processing instructions and comments.</p>[0m
[30;1m118 | [0m[35m<p>All operations that you run on such an ElementTree (like XPath, XSLT, etc.)[0m
[30;1m119 | [0m[35mwill understand the explicitly chosen root as root node of a document.  They[0m
[30;1m120 | [0m[35mwill not see any elements outside the ElementTree.  However, ElementTrees do[0m
[30;1m121 | [0m[35mnot modify their Elements:</p>[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1174[0m[34m of [0m[33m2617[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m

[30;1m732 | [0m[35m<p>Objectify uses two different types of Elements.  Structural Elements (or tree[0m
[30;1m733 | [0m[35mElements) represent the object tree structure.  Data Elements represent the[0m
[30;1m734 | [0m[35mdata containers at the leafs.  You can explicitly create tree Elements with[0m
[30;1m735 | [0m[35mthe <tt class="docutils literal">objectify.Element()</tt> factory and data Elements with the[0m
[30;1m736 | [0m[35m<tt class="docutils literal">objectify.DataElement()</tt> factory.</p>[0m
[30;1m737 | [0m[35m<p>When Element objects are created, lxml.objectify must determine which[0m

[30;1m113 | [0m[35m<p>The semantics of <tt class="docutils literal">_init()</tt> are as follows:</p>[0m
[30;1m114 | [0m[35m<ul class="simple">[0m
[30;1m115 | [0m[35m<li>It is called once on Element class instantiation time.  That is,[0m
[30;1m116 | [0m[35mwhen a Python representation of the element is created by lxml.  At[0m
[30;1m117 | [0m[35mthat time, the element object is completely initialized to represent[0m
[30;1m118 | [0m[35ma specific XML element within the tree.</li>[0m

[30;1m120 | [0m[35min exactly the same way as anywhere else in the program.</li>[0m

[30;1m262 | [0m[35m<h2>Attribute based lookup</h2>[0m
[30;1m263 | [0m[35m<p>This scheme uses a mapping from attribute values to classes.  An attribute[0m
[30;1m264 | [0m[35mname is set at initialisation time and is then used to find the corresponding[0m
[30;1m265 | [0m[35mvalue in a dictionary.  It is set up as follows:</p>[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1315[0m[34m of [0m[33m2617[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/lxml-5.3.2/doc/html/element_classes.html[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m193 | [0m[35m<h2>Default class lookup</h2>[0m
[30;1m194 | [0m[35m<p>This is the most simple lookup mechanism.  It always returns the default[0m
[30;1m195 | [0m[35melement class.  Consequently, no further fallbacks are supported, but this[0m
[30;1m196 | [0m[35mscheme is a nice fallback for other custom lookup mechanisms.  Specifically,[0m
[30;1m197 | [0m[35mit also handles comments and processing instructions, which are easy to[0m
[30;1m198 | [0m[35mforget about when mapping proxies to classes.</p>[0m
[30;1m199 | [0m[35m<p>Usage:</p>[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1316[0m[34m of [0m[33m2617[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m

[30;1m801 | [0m[35m<h2>Why can't lxml parse my XML from unicode strings?</h2>[0m
[30;1m802 | [0m[35m<p>First of all, XML is explicitly defined as a stream of bytes.  It's not[0m

[30;1m804 | [0m[35msequences and how to map them to text and structure.  That leads to rule[0m
[30;1m805 | [0m[35mnumber one: do not decode your XML data yourself.  That's a part of the[0m
[30;1m806 | [0m[35mwork of an XML parser, and it does it very well.  Just pass it your data as[0m

[30;1m431 | [0m[35m<h2>Why is lxml not written in Python?</h2>[0m
[30;1m432 | [0m[35m<p>It <em>almost</em> is.</p>[0m
[30;1m433 | [0m[35m<p>lxml is not written in plain Python, because it interfaces with two C[0m
[30;1m434 | [0m[35mlibraries: libxml2 and libxslt.  Accessing them at the C-level is[0m
[30;1m435 | [0m[35mrequired for performance reasons.</p>[0m
[30;1m436 | [0m[35m<p>However, to avoid writing plain C-code and caring too much about the[0m
[30;1m437 | [0m[35mdetails of built-in types and reference counting, lxml is written in[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1388[0m[34m of [0m[33m2617[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m

[30;1m404 | [0m[35m<h2>Why do I get errors about missing UCS4 symbols when installing lxml?</h2>[0m
[30;1m405 | [0m[35m<p>You are using a Python installation that was configured for a different[0m
[30;1m406 | [0m[35minternal Unicode representation than the lxml package you are trying to[0m
[30;1m407 | [0m[35minstall.  CPython versions before 3.3 allowed to switch between two types[0m
[30;1m408 | [0m[35mat build time: the 32 bit encoding UCS4 and the 16 bit encoding UCS2.[0m
[30;1m409 | [0m[35mSadly, both are not compatible, so eggs and other binary distributions[0m
[30;1m410 | [0m[35mcan only support the one they were compiled with.</p>[0m

[30;1m572 | [0m[35m<h2>How do I know a bug is really in lxml and not in libxml2?</h2>[0m
[30;1m573 | [0m[35m<p>A large part of lxml's functionality is implemented by libxml2 and[0m
[30;1m574 | [0m[35mlibxslt, so problems that you encounter may be in one or the other.[0m
[30;1m575 | [0m[35mKnowing the right place to ask will reduce the time it takes to fix[0m
[30;1m576 | [0m[35mthe problem, or to find a work-around.</p>[0m
[30;1m577 | [0m[35m<p>Both libxml2 and libxslt come with their own command line frontends,[0m
[30;1m578 | [0m[35mnamely <tt class="docutils literal">xmllint</tt> and <tt class="docutils literal">xsltproc</tt>.  If[0m

[30;1m565 | [0m[35mand libxslt that you get from the code snippet above.  If we do not[0m

[30;1m270 | [0m[35m<h2>What about that trailing text on serialised Elements?</h2>[0m

[30;1m273 | [0m[35mserialise an Element, you will get all parts of that Element:</p>[0m

[30;1m1914 | [0m[35m<dd><p>pre_delete and post_delete implicitly point to a place in the[0m
[30;1m1915 | [0m[35mdocument (where the two were split).  This moves that point (by[0m

[30;1m142 | [0m[35m<h2>The XPath context</h2>[0m
[30;1m143 | [0m[35m<p>Functions get a context object as first parameter.  In lxml 1.x, this value[0m
[30;1m144 | [0m[35mwas None, but since lxml 2.0 it provides two properties: <tt class="docutils literal">eval_context</[0m
[30;1m145 | [0m[35m<tt class="docutils literal">context_node</tt>.  The context node is the Element where the current f[0m
[30;1m146 | [0m[35mis called:</p>[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1612[0m[34m of [0m[33m2617[0m[31m ]--[0m
